Programming contests and their relative merits have been discussed and debated for a number of years among the computer community. It is generally felt that, by competing, students are afforded the opportunity to perform as a team under very tight constraints along with a chance to sharpen their programming skills• A variety of other rewards are derived -all of which should prove useful in later years• Bryson and Roth [i] in their January 1981 paper presented to the Education Board of ACM, considered the impact of programming contests upon students at the elementary and secondary level• In their discussion, the following questions were raised: